Overview

This sample program implements Custom Service Protocol over BLE to communicate with RSL10 Sense and Control Android or iOS mobile applications.

This example is meant to be used with the RSL10-SENSE-DB-GEVK evaluation board and exposes data from its on-board sensors:

  • NOA1305 - Ambient light sensor node providing ambient light readings in Lux.
  • BME680 - Environmental sensor node providing ambient temperature, relative humidity and atmospheric pressure data.
  • BHI160B with BMM150 - Smart sensor hub with external magnetometer providing Nine degrees of freedom orientation data.
  • Push button status - Example implementation of a custom node.

Hardware Requirements

Compatible evaluation boards:

  • RSL10-SENSE-DB-GEVK
    • 3V Lithium CR2032 battery is required for proper operation.
  • RSL10-SENSE-GEVK
    • 3V Lithium CR2032 battery is required for proper operation.
    • It is required to either solder 10-pin debugging header or use 10-pin needle connector to program / debug the board.
    • Debug probe is not included with the board.

Verification

After the program is flashed and running on RSL10-SENSE-GEVK board it will start connectable advertising over BLE. Android application RSL10 Sense & Control can be used to show data measured by device sensors. See Using mobile application section below for instructions on how to configure and use this application.

The RSL10-SENSE boards expose the following Sensors / Actuators in the application:

  • ALS-NOA1305
  • Environmental
  • Pressure
  • Humidity
  • Temperature
  • Gyroscope
  • Accelerometer
  • Magnetometer

Additional sensor values can be read by adding custom sensor components based on the IDK Custom Service specification. This specification can be found in the docs folder of the CMSIS-Pack.

Debugging Setup

Flashing program

  1. Build the project

  2. Refresh project

    Needed only once to make sure that Eclipse is aware of the built executable.

  3. Create debug configuration

    1. Open Debug configurations window (Run -> Debug Configurations).

    1. Create GDB SEGGER J-Link Debugging debug configuration by double clicking it in window.

    2. Press Debug button in the bottom right corner of the window.

    3. When Eclipse switches to debugging perspective press Resume button to run the program.

    1. Terminate the debugging session before attempting to:
    • Flash new program into the board.
    • Disconnect target board from debugger board or power supply.

The program loaded using debugger will be saved into RLS10 flash memory and will be automatically executed after the board is restarted.

Opening debug terminal

This application uses SEGGER RTT (Real Time Terminal) to print messages to host PC. To use RTT the target board has to be connected to PC by using Segger J-Link debug probe. Segger J-Link tools have to be installed on host PC.

A debug probe is provided with: * BDK-GEVK - As an on-board debugger. * RSL10-SENSE-DB-GEVK - As external board with 10-pin debug cable.

RTT is configured to work in non-blocking mode by default. Therefore it is not required to have RTT session opened in order to run the program.

  1. Open SEGGER RTTViewer terminal.

    Shortcut to it is located in Start menu in the SEGGER/J-Link Vx.xxx/J-Link RTT Viewer Vx.xxx folder.

    As of September 2018 it is recommended to use older V6.32x version of RTT Viewer. Newer V6.34x versions of RTT Viewer were found out to contain various bugs resulting in program crashes. RTT Client can be used with newer versions instead to show output messages with limited functionality.

  2. Connect to Target Device

    It might be required to disconnect and reconnect (File->Disconnect & File->Connect) when target board is restarted.

    It is also possible to use the Existing Session option if program is running through debugger in Eclipse.

  3. Switch to Terminal 0 tab to see messages from target device.

Using mobile application

  1. Open RSL10 Sense and Control application on your smart phone.

    Select receive mode if starting it for the first time.

  2. Switch to Receive over BLE mode.

    Open the settings page by clicking the gear icon in top right corner. The settings page needs to show:

    • Enable Broadcast slider is off
    • Manage Receive Channel is set to Receive via BLE

  3. Connect to running BDK_BLE_Terminal device.

    Each device is identified by its name and MAC address. Device can be assigned a custom name by clicking the three dots on right side.

    Device name can also be changed in the RSL10 program.

  4. Select components based on which shields are connected.

  5. Observe sensor data being received and updated in the app and logs in RTT terminal.

  6. Optionally save this configuration for quick access in the future.

Notes

Sometimes the firmware in RSL10 cannot be successfully re-flashed, due to the application going into Sleep Mode or resetting continuously (either by design or due to programming error). To circumvent this scenario, a software recovery mode using DIO12 can be implemented with the following steps:

  1. Connect DIO12 to ground by pressing the PB2 push button.
  2. Press the RESET button (this restarts the application, which will pause at the start of its initialization routine).
  3. Re-flash RSL10. After successful re-flashing, disconnect DIO12 from ground, and press the RESET button so that the application will work properly.
